questions.overhead_measurability:
**No, the claimed overhead values (0.5/0.4/0.3) cannot be measured with confidence from the provided material.**

The document asserts these figures were “MEASURED from VuDu logs,” yet offers no actual logs, timestamps, token counts, trial counts, or raw data. The sole concrete detail supplied is Claude’s 6,500-word bootstrap versus a 2,000-word baseline across five rounds; this single comparison is neither replicated nor statistically summarized, and the 0.5 figure appears to be a rough ratio rather than a defined metric with variance or confidence interval. The 0.4 and 0.3 values rest on even thinner descriptions (“empirical validation time,” “pattern analysis”) without any observable quantities attached.

Valid measurement would require:
- an operational definition of overhead (extra tokens, wall-clock time, or decision cycles) fixed before data collection;
- repeated, controlled trials against an explicit baseline condition;
- transparent, timestamped logs that third parties can inspect and recompute;
- reporting of means, standard deviations, and sample size so uncertainty can be quantified.

Absent these elements, the numbers function as illustrative labels rather than empirical observations. The architecture document therefore fails its own “Evidence precedes acceptance” standard.
